    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n4142" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἕως, εἵως, εἷος</span></b> : (1) <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">as
            long as, until;</span> foll. by the usual constructions with rel.
          words (see <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἄν, κέν</span>). A clause
          introduced by <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἕως</span> often denotes
          purpose, <i><span class="en">Od. 4.800</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Od. 9.376</span></i>.—(2) like <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">τέως</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">for a while</span>, usually with <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέν</span>, <i><span class="en">Od.
            2.148</span></i>, etc. —<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἕως</span>, to be read
          with ‘synizesis,’ except <i><span class="en">Od.
          2.78</span></i>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
